        <h3 data-uuid="8e579135c5a344b19d77ef15785557fb">1866 Elections</h3>
        <p data-uuid="a412df1797414271a72eabba3d14763b">President Johnson and most Democrats opposed the Fourteenth Amendment. As a result, civil rights for African Americans became a key issue in the 1866 congressional elections. To help the Democrats, Johnson traveled around the country defending his Reconstruction plan. Johnson’s speaking tour was a disaster. It did little to win votes for the Democratic Party. Johnson even got into arguments with people in the audiences of some of his speaking engagements.</p>
        <section data-uuid="0b569e16a04746bc82ab3d83c0040df9" class="historical-source nobg">
            <article data-uuid="d3134354e2e84814a790a0a8e067c252" class="box gradient">
                <div data-uuid="297682fdd7904458a016373ce11f32d1" class="header-element">
                    <h2 data-uuid="1b2286485bf148b0a88d8e5ae0ef894c" class="label">Historical Source</h2>
                </div>
                <div data-uuid="d5a1a7a3c2bd48eda3453b809e9ce466" class="jonra">
                    <h2 data-uuid="61d23d901b19431296cfc31dfad07ee3">“Andrew Johnson’s Reconstruction and How it Works” by Thomas Nast</h2>
                    <p data-uuid="727550579eff42f0a71a026e28623522" class="source">With this attention-grabbing cartoon, Thomas Nast wanted both to generate opposition to President Andrew Johnson’s lenient Reconstruction plan and to gain support in the fall 1866 elections for Republican congressional candidates who endorsed a more radical approach to Reconstruction.</p>
                </div>
